\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
from wiki about interchange of limiting operations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
interchange of limiting operations - 
\series bold
mathematical analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 are two given limiting operations cannot be assumed to give the same result
 when applied in either order.
 Historical sources for this theory is the study of 
\series bold
trigonometric series
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conclusions that assume limiting operations do 'commute' are called 
\emph on
formal
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
G.
 H.
 Hardy wrote that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The problem of deciding whether two given limit operations are commutative
 is one of the most important in mathematics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 An opinion apparently not in favour of the piece-wise approach, but of
 leaving analysis at the level of heuristic, was that of Richard Courant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
uniform convergence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
counterexamples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
double sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{m,n}$
\end_inset

 defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{m,n}=2^{m-n}
\]

\end_inset

is not the case that the operations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{m\to\infty}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}$
\end_inset

 can be interchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
List of related theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
